<Layout title="Section 3 – Infection Control">
  <h1>Section 3: Infection Control</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.3 – Demonstrates Sterile Techniques for Infection Control</em></p>
  <p>
    Demonstrate effective hand hygiene, equipment use for infection control, sterile and
    non-sterile gloving, PPE, and maintaining a sterile field.
  </p>

  <h2>Hand Hygiene</h2>
  <p>Hand hygiene is the single most effective way to prevent healthcare-associated infections (HAIs).</p>
  <h3>WHO 5 Moments for Hand Hygiene</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Before touching a patient</li>
    <li>Before clean/aseptic procedures</li>
    <li>After body-fluid exposure</li>
    <li>After touching a patient</li>
    <li>After touching patient surroundings</li>
  </ol>
  <ul>
    <li>Use <strong>alcohol-based hand rub (ABHR)</strong> for most clinical situations.</li>
    <li>Use <strong>soap and water</strong> when hands are visibly soiled or after caring for a patient with <em>Clostridioides difficile</em>.</li>
    <li>Wash with soap and water for at least <strong>20 seconds</strong>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Transmission-Based Precautions</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Route</th><th>PPE Required</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Standard</strong></td><td>Blood, body fluids, non-intact skin</td><td>Gloves; mask/gown/goggles if splash risk</td><td>All patients</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Contact</strong></td><td>Direct / indirect contact</td><td>Gloves &amp; gown</td><td>MRSA, VRE, C. diff, scabies</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Droplet</strong></td><td>Respiratory droplets &gt; 5 µm</td><td>Surgical mask (within 3 ft), eye protection</td><td>Influenza, pertussis, meningitis</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Airborne</strong></td><td>Droplet nuclei ≤ 5 µm</td><td>N95 respirator, negative-pressure room</td><td>TB, measles, varicella</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ PPE Sequence</strong>
    Don PPE before entering the room. Doff carefully to avoid self-contamination: remove
    gloves first, perform hand hygiene, then remove gown, mask, and goggles in the correct sequence.
  </div>

  <h2>Sterile vs. Clean Technique</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Technique</th><th>When Used</th><th>Key Principles</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Surgical aseptic (sterile)</strong></td><td>Invasive procedures (catheter insertion, wound care, IV start)</td><td>No microorganisms; sterile field must be maintained</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Medical aseptic (clean)</strong></td><td>Most bedside care activities</td><td>Reduces number of microorganisms; breaks chain of infection</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Principles of Sterile Technique</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>A sterile field becomes contaminated if touched by a non-sterile object.</li>
    <li>Any item below the level of the sterile field is considered contaminated.</li>
    <li>A sterile field must be kept in sight at all times.</li>
    <li>Moisture contaminates a sterile field (strike-through contamination).</li>
    <li>Edges of a sterile field (1 inch border) are considered contaminated.</li>
    <li>When in doubt — throw it out.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Gloving</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Non-sterile gloving:</strong> Don gloves when contact with blood, body fluids, or non-intact skin is anticipated; change between patients; perform hand hygiene after removal.</li>
    <li><strong>Sterile gloving:</strong> Required for invasive procedures; use open or closed gloving technique; maintain sterility during and after donning.</li>
  </ul>

